<div id="review_2389667326" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2389667326" />
    <a title="Nathaniel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3809399-nathaniel"><img alt="Nathaniel" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2389667326?book_show_action=true">May 12, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nathaniel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nathaniel" href="/user/show/3809399-nathaniel">Nathaniel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/31558712-the-collected-stories-of-arthur-c-clarke">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3809399-nathaniel?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2389667326" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5305191153798168015">When I picked this book up on an Audible sale, I didn&apos;t realize it was the <em>complete</em> collected stories of Arthur C. Clarke. I&apos;m still not 100% sure that it is, but at about 50 hours of content, it ought to be pretty close!<br/><br/>So it took me a while to get through--over a week, which is unusual--but I&apos;m glad I did. I learned a lot.<br/><br/>The first thing I learned is that early Arthur C. Clarke stories were not very good. The quality goes up considerably, however, and after the first decade or so of stories th</span>
  <span id="freeText5305191153798168015" style="display:none">When I picked this book up on an Audible sale, I didn't realize it was the <em>complete</em> collected stories of Arthur C. Clarke. I'm still not 100% sure that it is, but at about 50 hours of content, it ought to be pretty close!<br /><br />So it took me a while to get through--over a week, which is unusual--but I'm glad I did. I learned a lot.<br /><br />The first thing I learned is that early Arthur C. Clarke stories were not very good. The quality goes up considerably, however, and after the first decade or so of stories they are so good that I'm really surprised. The only Clarke I've tried to read--other than a few of these short stories--are novels like Rendezvous with Rama and 2001, neither of which I could get through because of how badly they were written. (The Dirty Old Man Syndrome factor in Rama was also very high.) When Clarke was on his game, his stories were <em>good</em>.<br /><br />The second thing I learned was how often ideas were repeated. Mostly, I'm talking about Clarke returning to the same concept for multiple stories, such as the last human watching glaciers overtake the planet and wipe out human civilization. There are at least two of these stories, among several that fit the more general "last human watches end of civilization" theme. There are also several "superior race kills all humans (or appears set to do so)", and at least two of those involved termites specifically.<br /><br />It's true even if we're talking about the genre as a whole, however, and not just specifically Clarke's stories. It's kind of depressing how many of the mainstays of sci-fi go back to Clarke. I knew the idea of putting people in a simulated reality that is so beautiful they don't want to leave wasn't new in The Matrix, but I didn't realize how far it went back. (I'm not sure if Clarke was first either, but The Lion of Comarre (Clarke's story) goes back to the 1960s. Other bid ideas that Clarke covered in old stories include animosity between machine-based and biologically-based intelligence and the fracturing of humanity in the future, especially as cynbernetically-enhanced humans drift away from normal human concerns, foreshadowing all the post- / transhumanist themes.<br /><br />So, did I like the book? Yeah. Especially the middle section. It seems like a good template for a lot of author's careers. The early stuff is fresh and vivid and fun, but also lacking polish and making some kind of obvious mistakes. The middle stuff is the best. The later stuff tends to get weird as the author veers off into deeper exploration of ideas / themes that are perhaps more interesting to him than his audience at large.<br /><br />Anyway, I definitely feel like this increased my understanding of the sci-fi canon, and I'm glad I read it, but for someone who isn't as interested as I am in sci-fi as a genre, there's probably a Best Hits version that keeps the good stuff without being quite so... comprehensive.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5305191153798168015" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

