<div id="review_4183909" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4183909" />
    <a title="John Wiswell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/147818-john-wiswell"><img alt="John Wiswell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442531848p2/147818.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4183909?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Wiswell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Wiswell" href="/user/show/147818-john-wiswell">John Wiswell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Science fiction readers</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4183909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7335518300696836889">As far as I know Arthur Clarke occupies a level of science fiction that only Isaac Asimov shared. Every time he had a scientific idea or came across a new piece of science, he wrote a short story about it. If he encountered several ideas and couldn&apos;t disentangle them, he&apos;d write a novel about them. Clarke breaks from Asimov in that his prose a bit more fluid, his subject-matter is sometimes treated too abstractly for perfect translation into his storytelling (such as the one-sided wall in the fi</span>
  <span id="freeText7335518300696836889" style="display:none">As far as I know Arthur Clarke occupies a level of science fiction that only Isaac Asimov shared. Every time he had a scientific idea or came across a new piece of science, he wrote a short story about it. If he encountered several ideas and couldn't disentangle them, he'd write a novel about them. Clarke breaks from Asimov in that his prose a bit more fluid, his subject-matter is sometimes treated too abstractly for perfect translation into his storytelling (such as the one-sided wall in the first story of this collection), and he has more of a penchant for the philosophical or religious (going to regions like a future when everyone is vegetarian and is disgusted by carnivores for a humorous monologue, and to a computer program that will give us God's true name and thereby, perhaps, end the universe). Because he was a man of sciences and philosophies, there aren't too many memorable characters in this 900+ page compendium, there is a lot of thought-provoking science fiction. His style is outdated, but his heart and intellect will always live on in his vast influence on the genre. This collection is an excellent introduction to one of Science Fiction's most prolific and important writers, giving you dozens of brief opportunities to sample his prose and approaches without diving into a full novel. As it is his complete short fiction, it ought to have anything your friends recommend reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7335518300696836889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


